s ticket pulls it back.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The Intent clarity HIGH rating does not specify which skill (discovery or lifecycle) becomes canonical for orchestrator-review.md, nor the criterion for choosing, despite the two files differing in length (133 vs. 172-184 lines).", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The child ticket bundles a 4th item (injection-resistance paragraph 5× in skills/research/SKILL.md) that does not appear in the parent epic body's reference-file-duplication headline finding — it would more naturally fit under 'Sub-agent dispatch duplicates artifact content' or a separate prompt-fragment finding.", "origin": "alignment"}], "dispositions": {"apply": 0, "dismiss": 7, "ask": 2}, "applied_fixes": [], "dismissals": [{"finding_index": 0, "rationale": "The 'inlined OR research-justified' fork is the deliberate intent, not ambiguity — the source explicitly routes this decision to the research phase via the Research hooks question on inline-vs-keep tradeoff."}, {"finding_index": 1, "rationale": "The line-range hedge is the deliberate intent: the ticket explicitly anticipates that #179's spec line ranges may have shifted and routes re-validation to research. Either ~210 or a research-documented different target is acceptable."}, {"finding_index": 2, "rationale": "Verifying the substitution mechanism is explicitly named as a Research hook. The intent (deduplicate the 5× paragraph) is clear; the mechanism is a research question with no scope-expansion bypass written into the ticket."}, {"finding_index": 4, "rationale": "The Open Decision escape hatch has a well-defined protocol: surface, not unilaterally re-scope. This is responsible boundary-setting, not a soft boundary."}, {"finding_index": 5, "rationale": "Closure-quality is owned by ticket #194 (the systemic investigation). The parent epic explicitly carves it out as separate from #179's narrow remediation scope."}, {"finding_index": 6, "rationale": "The size-cap convention applies as remediation when SKILL.md exceeds the cap; it does not mandate that all content live in references. Inlining trivially-small reference content when no over-cap pressure exists is consistent with the 'workflow trimming' philosophy and does not conflict with the size-cap convention."}, {"finding_index": 7, "rationale": "The canonical-home choice is a research-phase determination via the #172/#174 precedent and content examination of the two orchestrator-review.md files. The decision criterion (which content is more canonical or current) is discoverable by reading both files — not a user-decision."}], "status": "ok"}
